Abstract:
Accurate prediction of the resilient modulus (
) of subgrade soil is crucial for road structural design and ensuring long-term subgrade performance. However, existing prediction methods still exhibit significant shortcomings in testing efficiency, generalization capability, and interpretability. To address these issues, this paper proposed a hybrid prediction model (MCI-XGBoost-RC) based on the modified consistency index model (MCI) and Bayesian-optimized XGBoost (BO-XGBoost) residual compensation. By integrating physical prior knowledge with data-driven methods, the MCI-XGBoost-RC was suitable for multiple soil types and small-sample scenarios. Using 16 soil samples (totaling 990 
 test data points), the performance of six base models and algorithms (MCI, SVR, DTR, AdaBoost, BRR, and XGBoost) and four hybrid models (MCI-XGBoost-RC, MCI-AdaBoost-RC, MCI-DTR-RC, and MCI-SVR-RC) was systematically compared. Based on ablation experiments, the contributions of each module within the MCI-XGBoost-RC model were quantitatively evaluated. The effectiveness of the proposed prediction model was validated through interpretability analysis. Results indicate that across the entire dataset, MCI-XGBoost-RC (R2 = 0.975) outperformed other hybrid models (by 4%-25%) and XGBoost (R2 = 0.937) for the test set. At the sub-dataset level, except for dataset 16, the MCI-XGBoost-RC consistently maintained a R2 ranging from 0.91 to 0.99 across all other soil samples. This indicates that the hybrid MCI-XGBoost-RC model demonstrated superior generalization capability over both MCI and the purely data-driven XGBoost model. SHAP analysis further validated that the decision-making mechanism of the proposed model aligned with the physical understanding of resilient modulus. Furthermore, by incorporating the hybrid model, this study proposed an LLM-driven Agent framework capable of generating comprehensive diagnostic reports, demonstrating a paradigm shift from simple numerical fitting to intelligent engineering decision support. This study provides a reliable design tool for subgrade engineering that combines high-precision prediction capability with physical interpretability, facilitating structural design and material optimization in practical engineering.
